linked image syntax looks like this:

𝐖𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞 𝐒𝐩𝐚𝐜𝐞 (or negative space) is simply unmarked space in design. 

In a design composition it is 𝐬𝐚𝐦𝐞 𝐚𝐬 𝐮𝐬𝐞 𝐨𝐟 𝐬𝐢𝐥𝐞𝐧𝐜𝐞 in music. Without proportionate use of silence, music is unstructured. Similarly, without 𝐖𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞 𝐒𝐩𝐚𝐜𝐞, design is unstructured and difficult to consume. Therefore I recommend you to use 𝐖𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞 𝐒𝐩𝐚𝐜𝐞.
</string>
			</dict>

&lt;i&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;/label&gt; &lt;h1 class="dn"&gt;MediaKit&lt;br&gt;User Guide&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;div id="toc"&gt; &lt;a href="#ban" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;Banners&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#mock" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;Mockups&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#mark" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;Markup&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#coll" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;Collages&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#vdp" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;Video Players&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#bad" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;Badges&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#prep" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;Prepare&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#upld" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;Upload &amp;amp; Markdown&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#wsp" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;White Space&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="#mymk" class="dn colorfultwo toc-links"&gt;My MediaKit&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="intro"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="introduction" style="padding-bottom: 0"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Welcome to MediaKit&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;This shortcut was developed for the makers of shortcuts. You spend hours of time to create and develop shortcuts. You shouldn't spend another hour or more presenting your work. &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; offers you everything you need to showcase your shortcuts.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;Banners&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Create banners with the background color of your shortcut, the name and a short description or a slogan to introduce your shortcut.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#ban"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;Mockups&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Generate mockups with your screenshots and the frames of 50 iPhone devices and 34 iPad devices.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#mock"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;Markup&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Add notes to your mockups or highlight specific areas to direct users' attention.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#mark"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;Collages&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;After you have created your mockups, you can merge several graphics into one. You have the choice to arrange them horizontally, vertically or as a grid.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#coll"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;Video Players&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;You have created a video for your shortcut and want to link it with highest attention? Create a YouTube-, Vimeo- or RoutineHub-Player with or without a video poster and link the graphic to your video.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#vdp"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;Badges&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Create your own Apple-style badges, for example to draw attention to which app is needed to use your shortcut. Or link another shortcut which is needed to use yours. You can also use this feature to show that you are the author.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#bad"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;Prepare&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Prepare your graphics for uploading to Imgur and embedding on RoutineHub. This guarantees that all &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; graphics have an accurate size and fit perfectly into the RoutineHub page of your shortcut.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#prep"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;Upload &amp;amp; Mark&amp;shy;down&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Upload your graphics directly to Imgur—anonymously and without the need to create an account. &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; also takes care of the embed code for you. The code you need to embed graphics with Mark&amp;shy;down is automatically generated and copied to your clipboard.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#mark"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;White Space&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;One of the most important things in design is white space. &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; offers you five different sizes to optimize your RoutineHub page layout.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#wsp"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="teaser"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn"&gt;My MediaKit&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;With &lt;b&gt;My MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; you always have your personal &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; collection at hand. Store and manage your graphics and retrieve them easily at any time.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a class="lm colorfulone" href="#mymk"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;h2 class="dn rainbow notunderlined" style="margin: 100px 0 20px 0"&gt;Have fun using MediaKit.&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="ban"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="banners"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 140px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 20px -2px" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Banners&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;With this part of MediaKit you create banners that act as headers on the RoutineHub page of your shortcut. A banner contains the name of your shortcut, a short description or slogan and your name (this could be your RoutineHub username). The banner uses the background color of your shortcut to enhance the recognition value.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;In the first step you decide the background color. You can choose from the 15 colors, which are also available in the Shortcuts app.&lt;p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now please enter the name of your shortcut.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;In the third step you insert the short description. You can theoretically leave this field blank, but this is not recommended.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;As the last step enter the author of the shortcut. If you have already entered your name in the import questions, you can skip this step by tapping &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;OK&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;That was it already. Your banner is generated and can be saved.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn notice" style="margin: 200px 0 60px 0"&gt;Please find below all banners in all available colors:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Apple&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Pumpkin&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Orange&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Amber&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Lizard&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Seafoam&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Turquoise&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Sky&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Azure&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Purple&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Violet&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Bubblegum&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Spacegray&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Gold&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="banwrap"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Silver&lt;/span&gt; &lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="mock"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="mockups"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 80px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 20px 0" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Mockups&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;Mockups serve the purpose of giving the visitor of your RoutineHub shortcut page an impression of what to expect. You can also use mockups to support the description text. As you know, a picture says more than a thousand words.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Both &lt;b&gt;MediaKit iPhone Mockups&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;MediaKit iPad Mockups&lt;/b&gt; follow the same strategy: You decide which iOS device you want to use—no matter which iPhone or iPad generation you own. The easiest way, of course, is to select the device you used to take the screenshots. This way the picture dimensions fit perfectly to the frame. Many generations of iOS devices have the same aspect ratio. For example, an iPhone 8 Plus screenshot also fits into the iPhone 5c, 5s, 5SE, 6s, 6s Plus, 7, 7 Plus and 8 frames. Alternatively, you can take a look at the respective resolutions of the iPhones and iPads below and create your own graphics. Admittedly there is no serious reason to offer so many iOS devices, but we are known to be hunters and collectors…&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Whether you use &lt;b&gt;MediaKit iPhone Mockups&lt;/b&gt; or &lt;b&gt;MediaKit iPad Mockups&lt;/b&gt;, the steps are identical.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;First select a screenshot/graphic from your photo library.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;In the second step, select the iPhone/iPad frame you want to use for the mockup.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Your mockup will be generated and you can save it in your photo library.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle gold"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Gold&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle silver"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Silver&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle spacegray"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Space Gray&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad Air&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;1536 × 2048&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle silver"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Silver&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle spacegray"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Space Gray&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="visibility: hidden"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad 4&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;1536 × 2048&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle black"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Black&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle white"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;White&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad Gen 3&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;1536 × 2048&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle black"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Black&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle white"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;White&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="row"&gt; &lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad Gen 2&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;768 × 1024&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle black"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Black&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle white"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;White&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;768 × 1024&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle black"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Black&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle white"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;White&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="row" style="margin-bottom: 0"&gt; &lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad Mini 4&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;1536 × 2048&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle gold"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Gold&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle silver"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Silver&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle spacegray"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Space Gray&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad Mini 3&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;1536 × 2048&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle gold"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Gold&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle silver"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Silver&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle spacegray"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Space Gray&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad Mini 2&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;1536 × 2048&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle silver"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Silver&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle spacegray"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Space Gray&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="column"&gt; &lt;div class="device" style="margin-bottom: 10px"&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;iPad Mini&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h5&gt;768 × 1024&lt;/h5&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle black"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Black&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div class="circle white"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;White&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="mark"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="markup"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 65px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 20px -2px" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Markup&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;MediaKit Markup is no witchcraft, it's just another way to edit your mockups or collages. This part of MediaKit uses Apple's Markup tool that you've probably used before. Add notes with Markup, use geometric shapes to highlight areas, and so on—anything Apple's Markup can do.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Select one or more images from your photo library.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now you can use the Markup tool for all your images. When you're done, just tap &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Done&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="coll"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="collages"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 100px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 20px 0" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Collages&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;Using MediaKit Collages offers the advantage that you can display several mockups side by side on RoutineHub, for example to visualize a step sequence better. You can also control the size of the published graphics in this way. This can be done horizontally as well as vertically. Alternatively you can also create a grid.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;In the first step you decide on the desired orientation of the mockups. You can choose between horizontal (&lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Portrait Mockups&lt;/span&gt;), vertical (&lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Landscape Mockups&lt;/span&gt;) and grid (&lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Grid Mockups&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now choose how many mockups you want to arrange. You achieve this by specifying the number of repetitions.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;As the third step you select the mockups you want to combine. If, for example, you have chosen three repetitions, you will be asked three times to select a mockup. The Shortcuts app also offers multiple selection of images, but this way you have no control over the order. So by selecting your mockups step by step from the photo library, you decide the order yourself.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Afterwards your collage will be displayed. Simply place your finger on the graphic and swipe it away. The collage is automatically saved in your photo library.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="vdp"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="vidplayers"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 140px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 20px 0" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Video Players&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;If you've created a video for your shortcut, MediaKit Video Players is for you. Use this shortcut to create a video player style graphic. You can choose between a YouTube, a Vimeo and a neutral RoutineHub player.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you upload this graphic with &lt;b&gt;MediaKit Upload &amp;amp; Mark&amp;shy;down&lt;/b&gt;, a link to your video will be created. So you can easily advertise it on your shortcut page on RoutineHub.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;First you decide for a player design. Select &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;YouTube&lt;/span&gt;, &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Vimeo&lt;/span&gt; or &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;RoutineHub&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Next, you can choose if you want to use an image (called video poster) as background. Choose between &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Add Poster&lt;/span&gt; or &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;No Poster&lt;/span&gt;. If you choose &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Add Poster&lt;/span&gt;, you can import your graphic from the photo library. The format should be 1920 x 1080 px, which corresponds to Full HD.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now enter the title of your video or a catchy heading.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Finally enter the length of your video (for example: 09:41). Your &lt;b&gt;Video Player&lt;/b&gt; graphic will be created and you can save it in your photo library.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn notice" style="margin: 60px 0 100px 0"&gt;Please find below all available player styles:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;div class="vdprev"&gt; &lt;ul class="badul dwnld"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;YouTube Player,&lt;br&gt;Video Poster&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/jpg;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;YouTube Player,&lt;br&gt;No Poster&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/jpg;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Vimeo Player,&lt;br&gt;Video Poster&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/jpg;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Vimeo Player,&lt;br&gt;No Poster&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/jpg;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;RoutineHub Player,&lt;br&gt;Video Poster&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/jpg;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;RoutineHub Player,&lt;br&gt;No Poster&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/jpg;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="bad"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="badges"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 140px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 20px -2px" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Badges&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;Create your own Apple-style badges—the possibilities are nearly endless. For example, you can use a Classic Badge to identify yourself as the author of a shortcut on the RoutineHub page. You can also indicate that an app is required for your shortcut. And much more. With a Download Badge you have the possibility to link another shortcut which is needed to use your shortcut. This could be e.g. update shortcuts like UpdateKit, Check For Updates or UpdateHub.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b class="dn"&gt;Classic Badges&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;Create your own badges in white or black, with a border or without, with the Shortcuts app icon, with an icon from your shortcuts, a custom icon or with an icon of any app from the App Store.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b class="dn"&gt;Download Badges&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;Create badges in white or black with a download button in white, black or in the colors of your shortcuts.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you start &lt;b&gt;MediaKit Badges&lt;/b&gt;, you'll have the choice between those two options. Choose wisely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm" style="margin: 110px 0 11px 0"&gt;Classic Badges&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;With MediaKit &lt;b&gt;Classic Badges&lt;/b&gt; you can create your own badges, for example to draw attention to which app is needed to use your shortcut. You can also use this feature to show that you are the author of the shortcut. The possibilities are manifold, because you have practically all app icons from the App Store and all shortcut icons at your disposal. You can also use specially created icons.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;All badges are available with a white and a black background. For custom icons there is also the option to select a border. In total there are ten different possibilities (see below).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Before you decide on the design of your &lt;b&gt;Classic Badge&lt;/b&gt;, you must first create its content. A &lt;b&gt;Classic Badge&lt;/b&gt; is divided into three areas: Icon, Text, Name. For example, if you want to tell that your shortcut requires the app Instagram, you can enter "Requires" in the first step. Then enter the name, in this case "Instagram". In the last step you choose the design and the corresponding icon. That's it.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Enter a short text.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Enter a name.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Choose a design.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul class="nosteps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you have chosen the option &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Shortcuts Icon&lt;/span&gt;, the icon of the Shortcuts app will be added automatically and your badge will be generated.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you choose &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Shortcut Icon&lt;/span&gt;, a list of your shortcuts opens (in alphabetical order) and you can choose the shortcut that carries the icon you want to use. Your badge will then be generated automatically.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you choose &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Custom Icon&lt;/span&gt;, you choose an icon which you have e.g. designed yourself. Please note that it is not necessary to use the shape of an icon. It is sufficient if you use a square graphic. The icon shape is created by &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt;. This guarantees the correct radius. In addition, the option to use a border also works, because this is designed for the predefined radius. Ideally, you should only use the border if you prefer a white background and your icon has an equally white background. The same applies vice versa for badges with a black background and the use of an icon with a black background.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you decide to use an &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;App Icon&lt;/span&gt; from the App Store, you have two options: Search for an app by typing its name (you can also change the country of the App Store to find the icon of an app that may not be available in your country) or display a list with about 80 app icons. It contains 26 iOS apps and other known apps (in alphabetical order). Please note that you need a really fast internet connection to avoid waiting too long for the list to appear. The icons will all be downloaded live from the App Store. If the icon of an app changes one day, you will always have access to the current design. Tip: Be sure to check out the &lt;b&gt;MediaKit Prepare&lt;/b&gt; section before you plan to upload your badges and publish them on RoutineHub.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn notice" style="margin: 60px 0"&gt;Please find below all available Classic Badge styles:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;White Background:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ul class="badul"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Shortcuts Icon + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Shortcut Icon + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Custom Icon + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Custom Icon w/ Border + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;App Icon + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn" style="margin-top: 200px"&gt;Black Background:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ul class="badul"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Shortcuts Icon + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Shortcut Icon + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Custom Icon + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Custom Icon w/ Border + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;App Icon + Text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm" style="margin: 120px 0 11px 0"&gt;Download Badges&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;With &lt;b&gt;MediaKit Download Badges&lt;/b&gt; you can create your own badges with an integrated download button, for example to draw attention to which other shortcut is needed to use your shortcut. For these badges you will only have the option to choose the icons from your shortcuts, because that's what these badges are made for.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Download Badges&lt;/b&gt; are available with a white and a black background. If you like it subtle, choose the black or white download button. If you are more into colors, you have the option to color the download buttons. For this you can use the known colors of the Shortcuts app (see all examples down below).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Before you decide on the design of your &lt;b&gt;Download Badge&lt;/b&gt;, you must first create its content. A &lt;b&gt;Download Badge&lt;/b&gt; is divided into four areas: Icon, Text, Name, Download Button. For example, if you want to tell that your shortcut requires UpdateKit, you can enter "This Shortcut requires" in the first step. Then enter the name, in this case "UpdateKit". The third step lets you choose the design of the badge and its download button. That's it.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Enter a short text.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Enter a name.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Select an icon from your shortcuts&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Select a download button style.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul class="nosteps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you choose the option &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;White&lt;/span&gt;, the badge will have a white background and a black download button.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you choose &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Black&lt;/span&gt;, the badge will have a black background and a white download button.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you select &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;White, Color&lt;/span&gt;, the badge will have a white background and a colored download button. Choose a color for the download button. It should equal the color of your shortcuts' icon.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you select &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Black, Color&lt;/span&gt;, the badge will have a black background and a colored download button. Choose a color for the download button. It should equal the color of your shortcuts' icon.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Your badge will be generated and you can save it to your photo library.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/ol&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn notice" style="margin: 60px 0"&gt;Please find below some Download Badge examples:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ul class="badul dwnld"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;White Background,&lt;br&gt;Black Download Button&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;White Background,&lt;br&gt;Colored Download Button&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Black Background,&lt;br&gt;Colored Download Button&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;White Background,&lt;br&gt;Colored Download Button&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Black Background,&lt;br&gt;White Download Button&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Black Background,&lt;br&gt;Colored Download Button&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,￼"&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="prep"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="prepare"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 56px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 20px 0" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Prepare&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;With this part of MediaKit you prepare your graphics for the upload to Imgur. It is highly recommended to use this tool as it ensures that all MediaKit graphics fit perfectly on your shortcut page on RoutineHub.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Banners&lt;/b&gt; will be reduced to a size of 1200 pixels width. This ensures that the image remains a .png file while uploading the banner anonymously to Imgur (max upload size 1MB for non-animated images).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Single &lt;b&gt;Mockups&lt;/b&gt; are centered using a transparent background (2400 x 2400 pixels) and resized accordingly so they don't appear in full size on the RoutineHub page of your shortcut (because that's damn big). If you want your single mockups to appear in full size, you don't need this step and can upload them directly to Imgur using &lt;b&gt;MediaKit Upload &amp; Markdown&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Your &lt;b&gt;Collages&lt;/b&gt; will be reduced to a width of 2400 pixels. This ensures that the graphics are sharply displayed on a retina display.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Classic Badges&lt;/b&gt; are not only reduced in size, but also combined with a transparent template so that each badge on RoutineHub has the same size no matter how long the badge is. In addition you can align your badges (left, center, right). The same goes with &lt;b&gt;Download Badges&lt;/b&gt; (except the alignment option).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Video Players&lt;/b&gt; don't need to be prepared. They already have the perfect size.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;First choose whether you want to prepare a &lt;b&gt;Banner&lt;/b&gt;, a &lt;b&gt;Mockup&lt;/b&gt;, a &lt;b&gt;Collage&lt;/b&gt;, a &lt;b&gt;Classic Badge&lt;/b&gt; or a &lt;b&gt;Download Badge&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;For &lt;b&gt;Banners&lt;/b&gt;, &lt;b&gt;Mockups&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;Collages&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;Download Badges&lt;/b&gt;, all you have to do is select your graphics from the photo library. They are automatically resized to the correct size and then saved. The same applies to &lt;b&gt;Classic Badges&lt;/b&gt;, but here you can decide in a further step whether they should be left, centered or right aligned. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now you are ready for &lt;b&gt;MediaKit Upload &amp;amp; Mark&amp;shy;down&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ol&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="upld"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="upload"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 130px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 22px -2px" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;Upload &amp;amp; Mark&amp;shy;down&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;With this part of MediaKit you have a small tool at your disposal, which automatically takes care of the upload of your graphics to Imgur—anonymously and without the need to setup an account. In addition, all direct links are retrieved and converted to Mark&amp;shy;down. The code is copied to the clipboard so you can paste it directly into the RoutineHub page of your shortcut to embed your graphics.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Mark&amp;shy;down code for embedding images looks like this:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;![alt text](https://i.imgur.com/yourimage.png)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt; &lt;p&gt;As you can see, it consists of an exclamation mark followed by alt text in square brackets and the path to the image file in round brackets. The alt text is displayed if the image cannot be loaded. For this reason, when running &lt;b&gt;MediaKit Upload &amp;amp; Markdown&lt;/b&gt;, you will be prompted to enter this alt text.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;In the first step you need to enter the alt text. You can upload multiple images to Imgur at the same time. The alt text will be applied to all these images.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Then select one or more images from your photo library. All images are automatically and anonymously uploaded to Imgur, the Mark&amp;shy;down code is generated and copied to the clipboard. Done.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Another step is required if you upload &lt;b&gt;Video Players&lt;/b&gt; or &lt;b&gt;Download Badges&lt;/b&gt;: As these graphics act as a link, you'll need to enter a URL. Makes sense, right? The Mark&amp;shy;down code for linked images looks like this:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;[![alt-text](https://i.imgur.com/yourimage.png)](https://this.is/your/link)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt; &lt;p&gt;Don't worry, this code will be automatically generated. You only need to provide the link.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="wsp"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="wspace"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 65px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 20px 0" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;White Space&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;White Space in design composition is same as use of silence in a musical composition. Without proportionate use of silence, music is unstructured; some may call it noise. Similarly, without white space, design is unstructured and difficult to consume.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;White space or negative space is simply unmarked space in design. It is the space between the layouts, lines of paragraphs, between paragraphs, between different user interface elements and so on.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;While aesthetics is one of the benefits, others revolve around tangible impacts on the effectiveness of the page. In other words, white space significantly boosts not only user interface but also user experience of the page.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;With &lt;b&gt;MediaKit White Space&lt;/b&gt; there are five different sizes to choose from: &lt;table class="dn"&gt; &lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Extra Large&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;820px&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Large&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;580px&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Medium&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;480px&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Small&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;290px&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Extra Small&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;200px&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;MediaKit White Space&lt;/b&gt; is very easy to use:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Just choose one of the sizes, tap on the menu button and the corresponding code will be copied to your clipboard.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;You can then paste the content into the Mark&amp;shy;down Editor while creating a shortcut description on RoutineHub.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="separator" id="mymk"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="card borderbtm" id="mymediakit" style="padding-bottom: 0"&gt; &lt;div class="inner"&gt; &lt;img class="mkicon" style="width: 70px; height: auto; margin: 0 0 15px 0" src="data:image/png;base64,"&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn borderbtm"&gt;My MediaKit&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p class="rainbow"&gt;My MediaKit is your personal hub to store, manage and retrieve all the graphics you've created with the MediaKit shortcut collection easily at any time. To create your personal MediaKit collection, you'll only need the Mark&amp;shy;down code that is generated when you use MediaKit Upload &amp; Mark&amp;shy;down.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;The following functions are available:&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ol class="steps shrunk"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Access&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Preview&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Add&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Edit&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Remove&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Reset&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;h3 class="dn"&gt;Instructions&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;ol class="steps"&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Access&lt;/b&gt; your graphics and copy the Markdown code to the clipboard. Just select an entry, the rest will be done automatically. Now you can paste the copied code into the editor on the RoutineHub page of your shortcut.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Preview&lt;/b&gt; your graphics individually or in a group. If you have created a &lt;b&gt;Video Player&lt;/b&gt; or &lt;b&gt;Download Badge&lt;/b&gt; graphic, you can also test the respective link. Tap on a single entry to activate the individual preview or tap on &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Overview&lt;/span&gt; for a preview of all your &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; graphics.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Add&lt;/b&gt; new graphics. Your clipboard will be retrieved. Ideally the corresponding Markdown code is already in your clipboard: After you have tapped &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Add&lt;/span&gt;, you will be asked to create a name for your entry. After that you can insert the Markdown code, which was generated with &lt;b&gt;MediaKit Upload &amp;amp; Markdown&lt;/b&gt; and is in your clipboard.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Rename&lt;/b&gt; your entries or replace old ones with new graphics: If you tap on &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Edit&lt;/span&gt; you can choose between &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Rename&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Replace&lt;/span&gt;. With &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Rename&lt;/span&gt; you can edit the titles of your entries. With &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Replace&lt;/span&gt; you replace your graphics or edit for example the download link of a &lt;b&gt;Video Player&lt;/b&gt; or &lt;b&gt;Download Badge&lt;/b&gt; graphic.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Remove&lt;/b&gt; unused graphics: If you tap on &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Remove&lt;/span&gt;, all existing entries of your &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; collection will be displayed. Simply choose which entry you want to remove. That's it.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Reset&lt;/b&gt; your entire &lt;b&gt;MediaKit&lt;/b&gt; collection—this step is irrevocable: If you tap on &lt;span class="arrow"&gt;Reset&lt;/span&gt;, all entries will be removed. Don't worry, you have to confirm this step clearly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;h2 class="dn rainbow notunderlined" style="margin: 100px 0 20px 0"&gt;Thanks for using MediaKit.&lt;/h3&gt;
